      "id": "summary",
      "title": "Summary",
      "html": "<div class=\"paragraph\">Atrioventricular (AV) block refers to impaired conduction of impulses from the atria to the ventricles. It is classified according to the degree of delay or interruption in AV conduction: first-degree, second-degree (Mobitz type I and II), and third-degree (complete) AV block.</div><div class=\"paragraph\"><strong>First-degree AV block</strong> is characterized by a prolonged PR interval (&gt; 200 ms) with 1:1 AV conduction. It is usually benign and often related to increased vagal tone, medications (e.g., beta blockers, nondihydropyridine calcium channel blockers, digoxin), or myocardial ischemia.</div><div class=\"paragraph\"><strong>Second-degree AV block</strong> is defined by intermittent failure of AV conduction:<ul><li><strong>Mobitz type I (Wenckebach)</strong>: progressive PR prolongation until a nonconducted P wave.</li><li><strong>Mobitz type II</strong>: sudden nonconducted P waves without prior PR prolongation, usually indicating disease in the His–Purkinje system and carrying a higher risk of progression to complete block.</li></ul></div><div class=\"paragraph\"><strong>Third-degree (complete) AV block</strong> is characterized by complete dissociation between atrial and ventricular activity, with escape rhythms arising from junctional or ventricular foci. It is frequently symptomatic (syncope, presyncope, heart failure, hypotension) and often requires urgent pacing.</div><div class=\"paragraph\">Common causes of AV block include degenerative conduction system disease (Lenègre or Lev disease in older adults), ischemic heart disease (particularly inferior or anterior myocardial infarction), cardiomyopathies, infiltrative disorders (e.g., sarcoidosis, amyloidosis), myocarditis, post-cardiac surgery, and medications that slow AV conduction.</div><div class=\"paragraph\">Management depends on the <strong>degree of block, symptoms, and hemodynamic status</strong>. Asymptomatic first-degree and Mobitz type I AV block often require only observation and review of medications. Mobitz type II and third-degree AV block frequently mandate <strong>permanent pacemaker implantation</strong>, particularly if associated with symptoms or wide QRS escape rhythms.</div>"
    },
    {
      "id": "overview",
      "title": "Overview",
      "html": "<div class=\"condensed-hidden paragraph\">See “<a class=\"api link--same-article\" href=\"#management-approach\">Management approach to AV block</a>” for a structured algorithm on acute stabilization and definitive therapy.</div><div class=\"paragraph\">AV block is best understood along two axes:<ul><li><strong>Anatomic level of block</strong> (AV node vs His–Purkinje system).</li><li><strong>Functional severity</strong> (delay, intermittent failure, or complete interruption of conduction).</li></ul></div><div class=\"paragraph\">The level of block has important prognostic and therapeutic implications: nodal block (e.g., first-degree, Mobitz I) is often reversible and vagally mediated, whereas infranodal block (Mobitz II, many complete blocks) usually reflects structural conduction disease and carries a higher risk of progression and sudden cardiac death.</div><div class=\"table-wrapper api table-wrapper-wide\"><table class=\"table\"><thead><tr><th>Degree of AV block</th><th>ECG findings</th><th>Typical level of block</th><th>Usual clinical significance</th><th>Initial management</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>First-degree</strong></td><td>PR &gt; 200 ms, 1:1 AV conduction</td><td>Usually AV node</td><td>Often asymptomatic, benign</td><td>Identify and treat reversible causes; review AV nodal–blocking drugs; observation if asymptomatic.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Second-degree Mobitz I</strong></td><td>Progressive PR prolongation → dropped QRS</td><td>AV node</td><td>Often transient; may appear with inferior MI, sleep, high vagal tone</td><td>Correct reversible causes, monitor; pacing rarely needed unless symptomatic or with hemodynamic compromise.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Second-degree Mobitz II</strong></td><td>Fixed PR intervals with sudden dropped QRS complexes</td><td>His–Purkinje system (infranodal)</td><td>Unstable; high risk of progression to complete block</td><td>Hospital admission, telemetry; early consideration of permanent pacemaker, especially if symptomatic or wide QRS.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Third-degree (complete)</strong></td><td>AV dissociation, P waves and QRS complexes independent</td><td>AV node or infranodal (depends on escape focus)</td><td>Often symptomatic (syncope, severe bradycardia, hypotension)</td><td>Immediate stabilization (atropine if nodal, temporary pacing if needed) and strong indication for permanent pacemaker.</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class=\"paragraph\" id=\"management-approach\">In the acute setting, management focuses on:<ol><li>Assessing <strong>hemodynamic stability</strong> (blood pressure, perfusion, mental status).</li><li>Identifying <strong>reversible causes</strong> (ischemia, electrolyte disturbances, drug toxicity, vagal stimuli).</li><li>Using <strong>atropine</strong> for symptomatic bradycardia when a nodal block is suspected.</li><li>Escalating to <strong>temporary pacing</strong> (transcutaneous or transvenous) if there is persistent instability, especially with infranodal block or complete heart block.</li><li>Planning for <strong>permanent pacemaker implantation</strong> when high-grade or symptomatic AV block persists or when Mobitz II or complete AV block is present without a clearly reversible cause.</li></ol></div>"
